00:07:21.512 --> 00:07:23.392
to be the first person to begin this session.

123
00:07:24.312 --> 00:07:28.042
So, to begin, animal testing has been considered

124
00:07:28.052 --> 00:07:31.972
essential throughout the entire duration of modern anticancer drug

125
00:07:32.032 --> 00:07:35.712
development. And the purpose of animal testing is primarily to assess safety

126
00:07:36.192 --> 00:07:40.082
in ways that safety cannot be assessed in humans or have not yet been assessed in

127
00:07:40.092 --> 00:07:44.052
humans. However, over the last 20 years

128
00:07:44.092 --> 00:07:47.692
or so, there has been a trend in reducing animal use in drug

129
00:07:47.742 --> 00:07:50.052
development. And there are many reasons for this.

130
00:07:50.452 --> 00:07:54.372
I won't be comprehensive here, but a few of them would be the ethical concerns with

131
00:07:54.412 --> 00:07:54.932
animal use,

132
00:07:55.812 --> 00:07:59.712
the low predictability of animal studies, and this is particularly true for

133
00:07:59.752 --> 00:08:01.672
certain types of products that are highly specific.

134
00:08:02.252 --> 00:08:05.662
And also, just the development of more relevant and predictive

135
00:08:05.932 --> 00:08:09.552
testing alternatives. And on this slide, I have listed some policy

136
00:08:09.572 --> 00:08:13.012
initiatives that have sought to increase the use of alternative

137
00:08:13.052 --> 00:08:15.581
methods and to limit animal testing.

138
00:08:16.132 --> 00:08:19.852
And these policy initiatives represent an evolution of earlier

139
00:08:19.912 --> 00:08:20.252
efforts,

140
00:08:21.092 --> 00:08:23.552
expanding both their scope and impact.

141
00:08:24.132 --> 00:08:27.912
Now, the most recent is the FDA's Roadmap to Reducing Animal

142
00:08:27.952 --> 00:08:31.741
Testing in Preclinical Safety Studies, which was released

143
00:08:31.872 --> 00:08:35.783
just last year in 2025. Now, the aim of the roadmap is

144
00:08:35.832 --> 00:08:39.712
to replace routine animal testing with modern alternatives

145
00:08:39.752 --> 00:08:40.793
within three to five years,

146
00:08:41.653 --> 00:08:44.772
making animal studies the exception rather than the norm.

147
00:08:45.352 --> 00:08:49.072
Now, a summary of all the ways FDA has promoted streamlined

148
00:08:49.112 --> 00:08:52.722
non-clinical development programs can be found at the link on this

149
00:08:52.792 --> 00:08:53.192
slide.

150
00:08:55.832 --> 00:08:59.672
While reducing animal use and increasing the use of alternative methods

151
00:08:59.992 --> 00:09:03.872
is a priority for all areas of drug development, the oncology

152
00:09:03.952 --> 00:09:07.882
community was poised to become a leader in reducing animal testing,

153
00:09:08.492 --> 00:09:12.312
and this is because of the unique considerations of oncology drug development.

154
00:09:13.032 --> 00:09:16.892
First, there has been a drive to streamline non-clinical development programs

155
00:09:17.192 --> 00:09:21.132
to avoid delays in developing anticancer drugs, and this, in

156
00:09:21.172 --> 00:09:23.552
effect, has reduced some types of animal studies.

157
00:09:24.612 --> 00:09:27.892
Second, patients with advanced cancer have different risk-benefit

158
00:09:28.012 --> 00:09:31.992
considerations compared to the general population, and with that comes the

159
00:09:32.032 --> 00:09:35.672
acceptance that fewer animal studies may be needed to assess

160
00:09:35.732 --> 00:09:36.052
risk.

161
00:09:36.892 --> 00:09:40.822
Third, patients with advanced cancer are closely monitored during

162
00:09:40.872 --> 00:09:41.612
clinical studies.

163
00:09:42.672 --> 00:09:46.292
These considerations have long been known, and guidances have been created to

164
00:09:46.332 --> 00:09:50.112
provide for a more flexible and tailored approach to non-clinical safety

165
00:09:50.172 --> 00:09:54.112
studies for anticancer drugs. These include the ICH S9

166
00:09:54.212 --> 00:09:57.012
and ICH S9 Questions and Answers guidance.

167
00:09:58.012 --> 00:10:01.972
These guidances specifically sought to avoid the unnecessary use of animals

168
00:10:02.272 --> 00:10:06.172
in accordance with the replacement, reduction, and refinement

169
00:10:06.252 --> 00:10:07.812
principles of animal use.

170
00:10:08.892 --> 00:10:12.812
Importantly, there is no evidence that the reduction in animal testing

171
00:10:12.822 --> 00:10:14.382
has compromised patient safety.

172
00:10:15.192 --> 00:10:18.932
In fact, there is even a scientific basis for these alternative testing methods,

173
00:10:19.452 --> 00:10:23.352
which may be more predictive and scientifically superior to animal

174
00:10:23.392 --> 00:10:26.812
testing in certain circumstances.

175
00:10:28.852 --> 00:10:32.832
One such way that the oncology community has championed the reduction in

176
00:10:32.892 --> 00:10:36.832
animal testing has been with the acceptance and the promotion of weight-of-evidence

177
00:10:36.972 --> 00:10:37.772
risk assessments.

178
00:10:38.812 --> 00:10:42.721
Weight-of-evidence risk assessments are comprehensive approaches to evaluating

179
00:10:42.832 --> 00:10:46.652
safety by combining multiple types of information rather than

180
00:10:46.692 --> 00:10:49.132
relying on a single study or a single test method.

181
00:10:50.312 --> 00:10:54.212
Weight-of-evidence risk assessments may include non-clinical and clinical

182
00:10:54.232 --> 00:10:57.152
data generated with the investigational product,

183
00:10:57.972 --> 00:11:01.832
literature-based assessments of potential toxicities based on the roles of the

184
00:11:01.872 --> 00:11:05.432
molecular target in normal physiological processes and disease

185
00:11:05.472 --> 00:11:09.192
settings, and may include new approach methodologies or

186
00:11:09.232 --> 00:11:09.712
NAMs.

187
00:11:11.172 --> 00:11:15.112
Weight-of-evidence risk assessments have been described in international and FDA

188
00:11:15.192 --> 00:11:15.772
guidances.

189
00:11:16.732 --> 00:11:20.472
These guidances describe when weight-of-evidence risk assessments can be

190
00:11:20.492 --> 00:11:23.852
applied and provide general principles for what types of data to

191
00:11:23.892 --> 00:11:27.112
integrate. I'll provide some examples on the next slide.

192
00:11:28.212 --> 00:11:31.632
Weight-of-evidence risk assessments have proven useful in assessments of

193
00:11:31.672 --> 00:11:35.632
reproductive toxicity, and weight-of-evidence risk assessments now commonly

194
00:11:35.672 --> 00:11:36.172
replace

195
00:11:37.032 --> 00:11:40.092
animal embryo-fetal developmental toxicology studies.

196
00:11:41.112 --> 00:11:44.872
Weight-of-evidence risk assessments have also replaced three-month general tox

197
00:11:44.932 --> 00:11:48.442
studies for select types of well-understood products, such as

198
00:11:48.452 --> 00:11:50.832
CD3 bispecific T-cell engagers.

199
00:11:54.372 --> 00:11:58.022
The use of weight-of-evidence risk assessments have been described in international

200
00:11:58.072 --> 00:11:59.362
and FDA guidances.

201
00:12:00.212 --> 00:12:03.812
On this slide, I've excerpted sections of three guidance documents to

202
00:12:03.852 --> 00:12:07.802
show how weight-of-evidence risk assessments can be applied in non-clinical

203
00:12:07.892 --> 00:12:11.428
drug development.First, the ICH S9

204
00:12:11.528 --> 00:12:15.208
questions and answers guidance describes circumstances in which a weight of

205
00:12:15.328 --> 00:12:19.028
evidence assessment of reproductive risk could be provided in

206
00:12:19.088 --> 00:12:22.948
lieu of embryo-fetal developmental tox studies in pregnant

207
00:12:23.248 --> 00:12:24.268
non-human primates.

208
00:12:25.427 --> 00:12:29.088
Second, the FDA reproductive toxicity testing guidance

209
00:12:29.488 --> 00:12:33.388
outlines circumstances in which a weight of evidence risk assessment

210
00:12:33.428 --> 00:12:36.348
may eliminate the need to conduct dedicated embryo-fetal

211
00:12:36.368 --> 00:12:40.168
developmental tox studies and describes the general

212
00:12:40.178 --> 00:12:43.628
principles for what types of data to include in the weight of evidence risk

213
00:12:43.688 --> 00:12:44.148
assessment.

214
00:12:45.368 --> 00:12:48.988
Third, the FDA oncology therapeutic radiopharmaceuticals

215
00:12:49.028 --> 00:12:52.848
guidance recommends an integrated risk summary to assess late

216
00:12:52.928 --> 00:12:56.488
radiation toxicities in patients with long life expectancies.

217
00:12:57.488 --> 00:13:01.068
These examples are just a few ways that weight of evidence risk assessments can be

218
00:13:01.108 --> 00:13:03.228
applied in non-clinical drug development.

219
00:13:06.828 --> 00:13:10.728
In addition to our work in regulatory review, our division at the FDA has been a

220
00:13:10.828 --> 00:13:14.328
leader in regulatory research, results of which have advanced

221
00:13:14.368 --> 00:13:18.148
the replacement, reduction, and refinement of animal use in

222
00:13:18.188 --> 00:13:19.368
oncology drug development.

223
00:13:20.538 --> 00:13:24.228
This regulatory research has been in key areas including CD3

224
00:13:24.248 --> 00:13:27.288
bispecific T-cell engagers, antibody drug conjugates,

225
00:13:28.148 --> 00:13:30.868
immuno-oncology products, and pediatric cancer drugs.

226
00:13:31.728 --> 00:13:35.118
Results of this research have been published and shared in public venues.

227
00:13:35.888 --> 00:13:39.118
Over the next two slides, I will highlight the impact of our research on the

228
00:13:39.188 --> 00:13:43.148
non-clinical development of CD3 bispecific T-cell engagers and

229
00:13:43.208 --> 00:13:47.178
antibody drug conjugates. For

230
00:13:47.208 --> 00:13:50.958
this project, our research sought to find opportunities to streamline the

231
00:13:51.008 --> 00:13:54.368
non-clinical development of CD3 bispecific T-cell engagers.

232
00:13:55.128 --> 00:13:58.468
In this project, we analyzed data from INDs and BLA

233
00:13:58.548 --> 00:14:02.468
submissions for CD3 bispecific T-cell engagers and determined

234
00:14:02.588 --> 00:14:05.928
how often animal tox studies were not being conducted.

235
00:14:05.948 --> 00:14:08.628
For example, due to lack of target binding in animals.

236
00:14:09.548 --> 00:14:13.468
Oftentimes, longer duration tox studies were not feasible due to

237
00:14:13.528 --> 00:14:15.758
immunogenicity and loss of drug exposure.

238
00:14:16.688 --> 00:14:20.588
In these cases, other available safety data and literature were found to be

239
00:14:20.628 --> 00:14:23.408
sufficient to inform chronic toxicity.

240
00:14:23.448 --> 00:14:27.178
Our research concluded three-month general tox studies were

241
00:14:27.208 --> 00:14:31.028
not warranted, and instead, weight of evidence risk assessments could assess the

242
00:14:31.048 --> 00:14:31.868
chronic effects.

243
00:14:32.868 --> 00:14:36.408
If there were a specific concern, it could be addressed through alternative methods

244
00:14:36.808 --> 00:14:38.728
such as NAMs or clinical monitoring.

245
00:14:41.208 --> 00:14:44.428
Our research in antibody drug conjugates sought to answer two key questions.

246
00:14:45.208 --> 00:14:48.448
First, are animal data predictive of toxicities in patients?

247
00:14:48.697 --> 00:14:52.208
And second, is a three-month tox study in non-human primates

248
00:14:52.348 --> 00:14:52.768
warranted?

249
00:14:53.768 --> 00:14:57.748
For this project, we analyzed data from IND and BLA submissions

250
00:14:58.028 --> 00:15:01.608
for antibody drug conjugates with cytotoxic small molecule payloads.

251
00:15:02.328 --> 00:15:05.888
We found the toxicities were due to the small molecule payloads, not the

252
00:15:05.968 --> 00:15:07.368
antibody portion of the molecule.

253
00:15:08.168 --> 00:15:12.088
We also found the longer-term tox studies were no more informative

254
00:15:12.108 --> 00:15:13.528
than the shorter-term tox studies.

255
00:15:14.488 --> 00:15:18.168
Our research concluded three-month general tox studies in non-human

256
00:15:18.208 --> 00:15:21.778
primates are not warranted, and if a three-month study was

257
00:15:21.828 --> 00:15:25.808
warranted, the study could be conducted in rodents only.

258
00:15:27.828 --> 00:15:31.488
In summary, this is a rapidly advancing area, and the policy

259
00:15:31.528 --> 00:15:35.508
initiatives will continue to accelerate the progress in reducing animal

260
00:15:35.528 --> 00:15:38.028
testing and promoting the use of alternative methods.

261
00:15:38.758 --> 00:15:42.558
This is most evident in the FDA's roadmap to reducing animal testing,

262
00:15:42.768 --> 00:15:46.408
which again aims to make animal studies the exception rather than the

263
00:15:46.468 --> 00:15:48.148
norm within three to five years.

264
00:15:49.368 --> 00:15:53.238
Second, the oncology community has been a leader in reducing animal testing,

265
00:15:53.748 --> 00:15:57.728
and this is not by chance. This is because of the unique considerations

266
00:15:57.948 --> 00:16:01.388
of oncology drug development, as well as the results of years of

267
00:16:01.468 --> 00:16:04.848
efforts to develop and promote the use of alternative methods.

268
00:16:06.128 --> 00:16:09.888
Other areas of drug development are looking to the oncology community to

269
00:16:09.928 --> 00:16:13.668
learn more about how to move forward with reducing animal testing and promoting the

270
00:16:13.728 --> 00:16:17.558
use of alternative methods. Weight of evidence risk assessments.

271
00:16:17.728 --> 00:16:20.528
These are powerful tools to reduce certain types of animal

272
00:16:20.588 --> 00:16:24.008
studies. These are comprehensive approaches and are no less

273
00:16:24.028 --> 00:16:26.088
informative than traditional animal studies.

274
00:16:26.668 --> 00:16:30.488
And notably, this is an area again where the oncology community has been a

275
00:16:30.528 --> 00:16:30.808
leader.

276
00:16:31.808 --> 00:16:34.648
And lastly, our regulatory research is science-based.

277
00:16:34.988 --> 00:16:38.818
It draws from primary data and has contributed to oncology drug development

278
00:16:39.008 --> 00:16:42.958
being the leader in the reduction in animal testing and promoting the use

279
00:16:43.008 --> 00:16:43.968
of alternative methods.

